        <div class="info-section">
          <h3>BMR vs RMR vs TDEE — What's the Difference?</h3>
          <p><strong style="color: var(--text-primary);">BMR (Basal Metabolic Rate)</strong> is the number of calories your body burns to maintain basic life functions — breathing, circulation, cell production, and temperature regulation — measured under strict clinical conditions: 12 hours fasted, 8 hours of sleep, in a thermoneutral environment. BMR accounts for roughly 60-75% of your total daily energy expenditure.</p>
          <p><strong style="color: var(--text-primary);">RMR (Resting Metabolic Rate)</strong> measures the same thing as BMR but under less strict conditions. You don't need to sleep in a lab or fast for 12 hours. Because of the relaxed protocol, RMR is typically 10-20% higher than BMR. Most online "BMR calculators" (including this one) actually estimate RMR using equations like Mifflin-St Jeor, but the term "BMR" is used by convention.</p>
          <p><strong style="color: var(--text-primary);">TDEE (Total Daily Energy Expenditure)</strong> is the total number of calories you burn in a day. It's your BMR multiplied by an activity factor that accounts for exercise, daily movement, and the thermic effect of food. TDEE is the number you need to know for weight management — eat below it to lose weight, above it to gain.</p>

          <h3>Factors That Affect BMR</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Age</strong> — BMR decreases roughly 1-2% per decade after age 20</li>
            <li><strong>Gender</strong> — Men typically have 5-10% higher BMR due to greater muscle mass</li>
            <li><strong>Body composition</strong> — Muscle tissue burns more calories at rest than fat tissue</li>
            <li><strong>Body size</strong> — Larger bodies require more energy for basic functions</li>
            <li><strong>Genetics</strong> — Can account for up to 5% variation between similar individuals</li>
            <li><strong>Thyroid hormones</strong> — Directly regulate metabolic rate; imbalances significantly affect BMR</li>
            <li><strong>Temperature</strong> — Both cold exposure and fever increase metabolic rate</li>
            <li><strong>Crash dieting</strong> — Severe calorie restriction can lower BMR by 20% or more (metabolic adaptation)</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Tips to Boost Metabolism -->
