      <!-- FAQ -->
      <div class="card faq-section">
        <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">What is BMR (Basal Metabolic Rate)?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">BMR (Basal Metabolic Rate) is the number of calories your body needs to perform basic life-sustaining functions like breathing, circulation, cell production, and nutrient processing while at complete rest. It represents the minimum energy your body requires to stay alive and accounts for about 60-75% of your total daily calorie expenditure.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">What is the difference between BMR, RMR, and TDEE?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">BMR (Basal Metabolic Rate) is measured under strict clinical conditions after 12 hours of fasting and 8 hours of sleep. RMR (Resting Metabolic Rate) is measured under less strict conditions and is typically 10-20% higher than BMR. TDEE (Total Daily Energy Expenditure) is your BMR multiplied by an activity factor, representing total calories burned in a day including exercise, digestion, and daily movement. For practical purposes, most online calculators estimate RMR but label it as BMR.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">Which BMR formula is the most accurate?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">The Mifflin-St Jeor equation is considered the most accurate for most people and is recommended by the Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics. The Katch-McArdle formula can be more accurate if you know your body fat percentage, as it accounts for lean body mass. The Harris-Benedict equation (revised in 1984) is the oldest but still widely used. All formulas have a margin of error of about 5-10%.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">How do I calculate TDEE from BMR?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">TDEE (Total Daily Energy Expenditure) is calculated by multiplying your BMR by an activity factor: Sedentary (&#xd7;1.2), Lightly Active (&#xd7;1.375), Moderately Active (&#xd7;1.55), Very Active (&#xd7;1.725), or Extra Active (&#xd7;1.9). For example, if your BMR is 1,600 and you exercise moderately 3-5 days per week, your TDEE would be approximately 1,600 &#xd7; 1.55 = 2,480 calories per day.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">What factors affect BMR?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">Several factors affect your BMR: Age (BMR decreases about 1-2% per decade after age 20), gender (men typically have higher BMR due to more muscle mass), body composition (more muscle = higher BMR), body size (larger bodies require more energy), genetics, hormones (especially thyroid hormones), climate and body temperature, and certain medications. You cannot change most factors, but increasing muscle mass through strength training is the most effective way to raise your BMR.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">Should I eat below my BMR to lose weight?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">It is generally not recommended to eat below your BMR for extended periods. Eating below your BMR can cause your body to enter a conservation mode, slowing your metabolism, losing muscle mass, and causing nutrient deficiencies. Instead, use your TDEE as a baseline and create a moderate caloric deficit of 500-750 calories below TDEE for sustainable weight loss of 1-1.5 lbs per week.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">How does the Katch-McArdle formula differ from Mifflin-St Jeor?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">The Katch-McArdle formula uses lean body mass (LBM) instead of total weight, height, and gender. The formula is: BMR = 370 + (21.6 &#xd7; LBM in kg). This makes it potentially more accurate for athletic individuals with higher muscle mass or anyone who knows their body fat percentage. Unlike Mifflin-St Jeor, it does not differentiate between genders because lean mass already accounts for body composition differences.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">How can I increase my BMR?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">The most effective way to increase your BMR is to build lean muscle through resistance training — each pound of muscle burns about 6-7 calories per day at rest compared to 2-3 for fat. Other strategies include staying well-hydrated, getting adequate sleep (7-9 hours), eating enough protein (which has a higher thermic effect), avoiding crash diets that lower metabolism, and staying active throughout the day.</div>
        </div>
